# 🎯 The Core Decision

👉 **Route TLS Mode vs Istio TLS Mode**

| Option          | Who handles TLS   |
| --------------- | ----------------- |
| **passthrough** | Istio Gateway ✅   |
| **reencrypt**   | OpenShift Route ❌ |

---

# 🧠 Key Principle (Very Important)

```text
In Service Mesh architecture:
👉 TLS must be handled by Istio, not by OpenShift Route
```

---

# 🔍 Architecture Comparison (With Example)

---

# 🟢 ✅ PASSTHROUGH (Correct for Istio)

### Flow:

```text
User → Route → Istio Gateway → VirtualService → MSTR
```

### TLS Flow:

```text
Client (HTTPS request)
   ↓
Route (does NOT touch TLS)
   ↓
Istio Gateway (sees original hostname ✅)
   ↓
VirtualService routes correctly
```

---

### Example Request

```text
https://mstr-env01.apps.company.com
```

👉 Istio receives:

```text
Host: mstr-env01.apps.company.com ✅
```

👉 VirtualService matches:

```yaml
hosts:
- mstr-env01.apps.company.com
```

✔ Routing SUCCESS

---

# 🔴 ❌ REENCRYPT (Breaks Istio)

### Flow:

```text
User → Route (TLS terminate) → Route (TLS re-encrypt) → Istio → MSTR
```

---

### What Actually Happens

```text
Client → Route
Route TERMINATES TLS ❌
```

👉 Now Route creates **NEW TLS session**

```text
Route → Istio
```

---

### Problem #1 — Lost Hostname (SNI)

Istio depends on:

```text
SNI (Server Name Indication)
```

👉 Original request:

```text
mstr-env01.apps.company.com
```

👉 After reencrypt:

```text
Istio sees: UNKNOWN ❌
```

---

### Result:

```text
VirtualService CANNOT match host ❌
```

---

### Problem #2 — Routing Failure

Istio VirtualService:

```yaml
hosts:
- mstr-env01.apps.company.com
```

But Istio receives:

```text
no hostname ❌
```

---

👉 Result:

```text
503 Service Unavailable ❌
```

---

### Problem #3 — TLS Mismatch

Route expects backend TLS like:

```text
Route → HTTPS → Backend
```

But Istio expects:

```text
TLS passthrough OR Istio-managed TLS
```

👉 Conflict:

```text
Double TLS layers ❌
```

---

# 🧠 Real-World Analogy (Easy to Explain)

Think of it like a **sealed envelope 📩**

---

## PASSTHROUGH

```text
Route = courier
Istio = recipient
```

Courier delivers envelope without opening:

✔ Message intact
✔ Recipient reads correctly

---

## REENCRYPT

```text
Route = courier who opens and rewrites letter ❌
```

Courier:

* Opens envelope ❌
* Writes new message ❌
* Sends again ❌

Recipient (Istio):

```text
"Hey… this is not what I expected" 😅
```

---

# 🔥 Deep Technical Reason (Important for Interview / Team)

---

## Istio Uses SNI for Routing

```text
TLS handshake includes hostname (SNI)
```

Example:

```text
Client → "I want mstr-env01.apps.company.com"
```

---

## PASSTHROUGH

✔ SNI preserved
✔ Istio reads hostname
✔ Routing works

---

## REENCRYPT

❌ TLS terminated at Route
❌ New TLS created
❌ Original SNI LOST

---

👉 Istio cannot route

---

# ⚖️ Side-by-Side Comparison

| Feature                  | PASSTHROUGH | REENCRYPT |
| ------------------------ | ----------- | --------- |
| TLS termination          | Istio       | Route     |
| SNI preserved            | ✅ Yes       | ❌ No      |
| Works with Istio         | ✅ Yes       | ❌ No      |
| Routing accuracy         | ✅ Correct   | ❌ Fails   |
| Complexity               | Low         | High      |
| Enterprise mesh standard | ✅ Yes       | ❌ No      |

---

# 🏢 Enterprise Best Practice

In **OpenShift + Service Mesh (Istio)**:

```text
Route = Layer 4 (TCP)
Istio = Layer 7 (HTTP/TLS logic)
```

👉 So:

```text
Route MUST NOT terminate TLS
```

---

# 🚀 Correct Production Design

```text
Client
   ↓
Route (passthrough)
   ↓
Istio Gateway (TLS terminate)
   ↓
VirtualService (routing)
   ↓
Application
```

---

# ❗ When REENCRYPT is OK

Use only when:

```text
No Istio involved
```

Example:

```text
Route → HTTPS backend service (Spring Boot, Nginx, etc.)
```

---

# 🏁 Final Answer (You Can Tell Your Team)

👉 **Why passthrough?**

* Preserves original TLS + hostname
* Required for Istio routing
* Avoids double TLS termination
* Industry standard for service mesh

👉 **Why NOT reencrypt?**

* Breaks SNI (hostname lost)
* Causes routing failure (503 errors)
* Conflicts with Istio TLS handling

---

# 💬 One-Line Explanation (for meetings)

```text
We use passthrough because Istio needs the original TLS and hostname (SNI) to route traffic correctly. Reencrypt breaks that flow by terminating TLS at the route, causing routing failures.
```

